3) Product Model (MVP – Locked)

3.1 Core principles
	•	No variants in MVP
	•	One product = one sellable item
	•	Product must support multiple industries (cosmetics, retail, services-as-products)
	•	Strong tenant isolation
	•	Designed to migrate to real variants later

3.2 Product entity (summary)

A Product represents one sellable item.

Key characteristics:
	•	Has its own SKU
	•	Has one price
	•	Has its own images
	•	Belongs to one primary category
	•	Can belong to multiple additional categories
	•	Can be linked to other products (pseudo-variants)

Key fields (conceptual)
	•	id
	•	tenant_id
	•	status (DRAFT | ACTIVE | ARCHIVED)
	•	name
	•	slug (unique per tenant)
	•	short_description
	•	price_cents
	•	currency (COP default)
	•	sku (auto-generated, editable)
	•	primary_category_id
	•	attributes (jsonb, flexible)
	•	timestamps

⸻

4) SKU Strategy (Locked)

4.1 Why SKU exists (even without variants)

SKU is required for:
	•	Merchant operations
	•	Receipts / invoices
	•	Inventory later
	•	Reporting
	•	External integrations later

4.2 Strategy
	•	SKU is auto-generated on product creation
	•	SKU can be edited/overwritten by merchant
	•	SKU must be unique per tenant when present

Generation model
	•	Tenant has a short code (e.g. COCO)
	•	SKU format example:

COCO-000123


	•	Sequence is per tenant

This removes friction while still allowing merchants with existing SKUs to use their own.

⸻

5) Pricing Model (MVP – Locked)

5.1 MVP pricing
	•	✅ price_cents (single price)
	•	❌ No discounts engine
	•	❌ No price lists
	•	❌ No variant pricing

This supports:
	•	Offline payments
	•	Wompi integration later
	•	Simple reporting

5.2 Future-safe decisions
	•	Pricing is stored at product level now
	•	When variants are introduced, price migrates to variant level using a default variant

⸻

6) Category Model (Locked)

6.1 Chosen approach

✅ Primary category + additional categories

This balances:
	•	Simplicity
	•	SEO
	•	Navigation clarity
	•	Merchandising flexibility

6.2 Category entity

Categories are tenant-scoped.

Key characteristics:
	•	Ordered (for menus)
	•	Slug-based
	•	Optional hierarchy (can be flat in MVP)

Category fields (conceptual)
	•	id
	•	tenant_id
	•	name
	•	slug
	•	description
	•	sort_order
	•	parent_id (optional)
	•	status

6.3 Product ↔ Category rules
	•	Every product:
	•	MAY have one primary category
	•	MAY belong to many additional categories
	•	Primary category:
	•	Used for breadcrumbs
	•	Used for canonical navigation
	•	Additional categories:
	•	Used for collections (Sale, Featured, etc.)

